    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Round off each of the following to one decimal place:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>45.672</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1.712</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>45.672</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We first place each digit in its correct place value position. 
                        </p>
                        <tabular bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium" top="medium">
                            <row header="yes" valign="middle">
                                <cell>Number</cell>
                                <cell>Tens</cell>
                                <cell>Ones</cell>
                                <cell>Decimal point</cell>
                                <cell>Tenths</cell>
                                <cell>Hundredths</cell>
                                <cell>Thousandths</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>45.672</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>4</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>5</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>.</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>6</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>7</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>2</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                        <!-- <p>
                            To round of  <m>45.672</m> to one decimal place,
                            we look at the digit in the hundredths place value. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Since the digit the hundredths place value is greater than
                            <m>5</m> we add <m>1</m> to the digit in the tenths place value.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, <m>45.672</m> correct to one decimal place is <m>45.7</m>
                        </p> -->
                        <p> 
                            To round <m>45.672</m> to one decimal place, we examine the digit in the hundredths place. 
                        </p> 
                        <p> 
                            The hundredths digit is <m>7</m>, which is greater than <m>5</m>. Therefore, we add <m>1</m> to the tenths digit. 
                        </p> 
                        <p> 
                            Thus, <m>45.672</m> rounded to one decimal place is <m>45.7</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1.712</m>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We first place each digit in its correct place value position. 
                        </p>
                        <tabular bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium" top="medium">
                            <row header="yes" valign="middle">
                                <cell>Number</cell>
                                <cell>Ones</cell>
                                <cell>Decimal point</cell>
                                <cell>Tenths</cell>
                                <cell>Hundredths</cell>
                                <cell>Thousandths</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>1.712</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>1</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>.</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>7</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>1</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>2</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                        <p> 
                            To round <m>1.712</m> to one decimal place, we examine the digit in the hundredths place. 
                        </p> 
                        <p> 
                            The hundredths digit is <m>1</m>, which is less than <m>5</m>. Therefore, we don't add <m>1</m> to the tenths digit. 
                        </p> 
                        <p> 
                            Thus, <m>1.712</m> rounded to one decimal place is <m>1.7</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Round off the following mass in kilograms correct to three decimal places:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4.7823</m> kg
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>4.7823</m> kg
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We first place each digit in its correct place value position. 
                        </p>
                        <tabular bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium" top="medium">
                            <row header="yes" valign="middle">
                                <cell>Number</cell>
                                <cell>Ones</cell>
                                <cell>Decimal point</cell>
                                <cell>Tenths</cell>
                                <cell>Hundredths</cell>
                                <cell>Thousandths</cell>
                                <cell>Hundred thousandths</cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>4.7823</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>4</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>.</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>7</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>8</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>2</m></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>3</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                        <p> 
                            To round <m>4.7823</m> to three decimal place, we examine the digit in the hundred thousandths place. 
                        </p> 
                        <p> 
                            The hundred thousandths digit is <m>3</m>, which is less than <m>5</m>. Therefore, we don't add <m>1</m> to the thousandths digit. 
                        </p> 
                        <p> 
                            Thus, <m>4.7823</m> rounded to three decimal place is <m>4.782</m>. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
